{{Quote|It is believed that through their bizarre alchemies, the Sith somehow stumbled upon the ability to manipulate mechanicals of complex nature through the Force: ships, computers, and, indeed, even droids.|Tam Azur-Jamin|<ref name="DTATF">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/81/indexp7.html|text=Droids, Technology and the Force: A Clash of Phenomena|int=Droids, Technology and the Force: A Clash of Phenomena (article)}}</ref>}}
'''''Mechu-deru''''' was a [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]] [[Force power/Legends|Force power]] that bestowed an intuitive understanding of mechanical systems upon the user. Invented by the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]], the technique allowed its practitioners to exert their influence over inanimate and [[Droid/Legends|robotic]] constructs. Through ''mechu-deru'', mechanical structures could be bound to the will of the user and imbued with the power of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] itself. The dark side power of ''mechu-deru'' also enabled the creation of [[Cyborg/Legends|machine-organic]] [[Sithspawn/Legends|Sithspawn]] [[mutant]]s called [[technobeast]]s.

The Sith origins of ''mechu-deru'' led to its avoidance by members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]], relegating its use to a small number of [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Technician/Legends|tech specialists]]. Even among the followers of the Sith, ''mechu-deru'' was an obscure technique practised by only a few at the time of its initial discovery. During the [[New Sith Wars]], the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord]] [[Belia Darzu]] used her own variant of ''mechu-deru''—dubbed ''[[mechu-deru vitae]]''—to create an [[Army/Legends|army]] of technobeasts by means of a [[Nanogene spore|nanogene virus]]. [[Standard century/Legends|Centuries]] later, the secrets of [[Lord/Legends|Lord]] Darzu were unearthed by [[Cronal]], a servant of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] who practised ''mechu-deru'' on mechanical devices and living subjects—himself included.

==Description==
A [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]] [[Force power/Legends|technique]],<ref name="CSWE-DARZU" /> ''mechu-deru'' allowed the user to manipulate mechanical systems through the power of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]].<ref name="NEGD" /> By means of a specially-designed [[Cybernetics/Legends|cybernetic]] [[Brain/Legends|brain]] implant, it was possible for a [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] individual to develop a mastery of ''mechu-deru'' at an accelerated rate.<ref name="TEP">{{GamerCite|5|The Emperor's Pawns}}</ref>

==Applications==
{{Quote|[Belia Darzu] learned the secrets of mechu-deru, the ability to transform the flesh of living beings into metal and machinery. She used this power to create an army of technobeasts: organic-droid hybrids bound to her will.|[[Hetton]]|<ref name="DBROT">''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Cronal_becomes_nothing.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The power of ''mechu-deru'' had the potential to backfire against the user.]]

The application of ''mechu-deru'' allowed the user to instinctively comprehend the inner workings of machinery and circuitry.<ref name="TJP" /> Through ''mechu-deru'', technology could be upgraded to suit a purpose beyond its original intended role,<ref name="NEGC">''[[The New Essential Guide to Characters]]''</ref> even allowing mechanical devices—including [[Droid/Legends|droids]]<ref name="NEGD" />—to [[Force sense/Legends|detect]] Force-attuned beings.<ref name="DOAE-3" /> Users were bestowed the ability to convert robotic machines into extensions of their will, overwhelming their internal circuitry.<ref name="NEGD" /> Attempting to posses the body of a [[Cyborg/Legends|cyborg]] would drastically transform the victim's cybernetics, enlarging them into a mass of tendril-like appendages.<ref name="CNE">{{Tales|19|Collapsing New Empires}}</ref> Such a practice, however, had the potential to backfire, causing the victim's mechanical prostheses to turn against the user.<ref name="DOAE-3" /> ''Mechu-deru'' was used to combine both the inanimate and the living, allowing the creation of part machine, part organic hybrids known as [[technobeast]]s.<ref name="DBROT" /> Using ''mechu-deru'', it was possible to imbue the technobeasts with the dark side of the Force,<ref name="CSWE-DARZU" /> binding them to the will of their creator.<ref name="DBROT" /> The technique allowed the applicator to rebuild and replace parts of their body with cybernetics.<ref name="DOAE-3" />

==Users==
===Sith invention===
{{Quote|This power, known as mechu-deru, was responsible for the creation of Belia Darzu's infamous Technobeasts, which were capable of rewriting an organism's entire genetic code.|Tam Azur-Jamin|<ref name="DTATF" />}}
[[File:Technobeast-NEGTD.png|thumb|left|170px|The technobeasts of Belia Darzu were created using ''mechu-deru vitae''.]]

[[Millennium/Legends|Thousands]] of [[Standard year/Legends|years]] before the [[Great Sith War/Legends|Great Sith War]], followers of the dark side-worshipping [[Sith/Legends|Sith Order]] discovered a way to manipulate mechanical structures through the power of the Force.<ref name="TOTJC">''[[Tales of the Jedi Companion]]''</ref> This technique—known as ''mechu-deru''<ref name="NEGD" />—was practised by only a small number of [[Sith sorcerer|Sith sorcerers]] at the time, causing its secrets to fade into obscurity. Nonetheless, the Sith practitioners of ''mechu-deru'' used the ability to create hybrids of metal and flesh known as technobeasts.<ref name="TOTJC" />

In [[1250 BBY]] during a subset of the [[New Sith Wars]] called the [[Sictis Wars]],<ref name="NEGD" /> a [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]] known as [[Belia Darzu]] researched ''mechu-deru'' alongside the dark side art of [[Sith alchemy/Legends|Sith alchemy]].<ref name="DBROT" /> In doing so, [[Lord/Legends|Lord]] Darzu created a [[Nanogene spore|technovirus]] capable of transforming living organisms into technobeasts. To produce these [[Sithspawn/Legends|Sithspawn]] creatures, Darzu devised and employed an alternative form of ''mechu-deru'' called ''[[mechu-deru vitae]]''.<ref name="NEGD" /> Using the power of ''mechu-deru'', Darzu imbued the creatures with the dark side,<ref name="CSWE-DARZU" /> binding an [[Army/Legends|army]] of them to her will. During her reign, the Dark Lord recorded her knowledge of ''mechu-deru'' inside a [[Holocron of Belia Darzu|Sith holocron]].<ref name="DBROT" /> The creation of Darzu's technobeasts ended when she was [[Assassination of Belia Darzu|assassinated]] by the [[Mecrosa Order]],<ref name="END">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/88/indexp2.html|text=''Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties''|int=Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties}}</ref> after which her secrets were thought to have been lost.<ref name="DBROT" />

In the era succeeding the New Sith Wars,<ref name="NEGD" /> the discipline of ''mechu-deru'' was practiced by the [[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Darth Maul/Legends|Darth Maul]]. In particular, Maul used the technique to modify a [[Protocol droid/Legends|protocol droid]] designated [[C-3PX]], transforming it into an [[Assassin droid/Legends|assassination droid]].<ref name="NEGC" />

===Imperial resurgence===
{{Quote|Flesh will be deconstructed into fuel. Machine will be reconstructed into art. Art will transform the galaxy!|Cronal|<ref name="CNE" />}}
[[File:Perek2.jpg|thumb|right|170px|Through ''mechu-deru'', the majority of Cronal's body was replaced with cybernetics.]]

[[Standard century/Legends|Centuries]] after the New Sith Wars, a number of [[Sith scroll/Legends|Sith scrolls]] containing the knowledge of Belia Darzu entered the possession of [[Cronal]], a dark side [[Darksider|practitioner]] who served the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]]. Intending to use the scrolls for his own purposes,<ref name="END" /> Cronal practised ''mechu-deru'' during his tenure as the [[Emperor's Hand/Legends|Emperor's Hand]], a personal agent of the [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Galactic Emperor]] [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]]. Using his knowledge, Cronal upgraded the [[thaissen crystal]]s that were installed into the [[Force detector|Force detecting devices]] used by Imperial [[Jedi hunter/Legends|Jedi hunters]]. This allowed the devices to determine the Force-sensitivity and alignment of a specific target.<ref name="DOAE-3" />

Following Cronal's failed Imperial [[Battle of Mindor|campaign]] on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Mindor/Legends|Mindor]], the [[Dark side adept/Legends|Dark Side Adept]] used ''mechu-deru'' to replace most of his body with cybernetics, leaving his head and neck as the only remaining organic parts. Around this time, Cronal spent years experimenting with both ''mechu-deru'' and Sith alchemy on the planet [[Trailia]], blending them to form his own method of creation dubbed the [[Stygian Art]]. In doing so, Cronal transformed the native [[Species/Legends|inhabitants]] into [[Trailian technobeast|technobeasts]], eventually traveling away with his creations to the world of [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]].<ref name="DOAE-3" />

At a later date, Cronal resided on the industrial planet of [[Andooweel/Legends|Andooweel]], having fully embraced ''mechu-deru'' under the new identity of "Perek". While basing his activities in an abandoned droid depot, Cronal was pursued by the [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] known as [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]]. During Skywalker's brief servitude under the reborn Emperor Palpatine, the Jedi Knight's cybernetic [[hand]] became polluted with the power of ''mechu-deru''. The alchemical alterations made to Skywalker's robotic [[Limb/Legends|limb]] ultimately lured him into a confrontation with Cronal. In an attempt to possess the Jedi Knight, Cronal infected the circuitry of Skywalker's hand with technobeast [[Nanogene droid|nanodroids]]. This attempt backfired, however, when the cybernetic hand turned against Cronal and strangled him to [[Death/Legends|death]].<ref name="DOAE-3" />

The power of ''mechu-deru'' was also wielded by [[Irek Ismaren]],<ref name="TEP" /> the son of another Imperial agent and dark side practitioner known as [[Roganda Ismaren/Legends|Roganda Ismaren]].<ref name="END" /> In the aftermath of Roganda's thwarted [[Ismaren plot|scheme]] against the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]],<ref name="TEP" /><ref name="COTJ">[[Children of the Jedi (novel)|''Children of the Jedi'']]</ref> she—like Cronal—would somehow acquire a number of Sith scrolls comprising the knowledge of the deceased Dark Lord Belia Darzu.<ref name="TEP" /><ref name="END" /> Around this time, Irek developed an accelerated mastery of ''mechu-deru'' by means of a cybernetic brain transplant, the [[subelectronic converter]]. Left to their own devices, the Ismarens had the potential to create and unleash a horde of part machine, part organic [[mutant]]s upon [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]].<ref name="TEP" />

===Jedi avoidance===
{{Quote|[...] the channeling of the Force through lightsabers and holocrons is a purely 'inobtrusive' act, unlike the aggressive manipulation of, say, mechu-deru.|Jedi Master Aqinos|<ref name="DTATF" />}}
Compared to the Sith, members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] were less willing to blend technology and the Force. Not wishing the tread the same path as the Sith, the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] diverted their attention away from ''mechu-deru'' and the study of droids.<ref name="NEGD" /> Despite this, certain members of the Order would still practice the technique of ''mechu-deru'', specifically [[Jedi Sentinel/Legends|Jedi Sentinels]] operating as [[Technician/Legends|tech experts]]. Such specialists were a rarity among the ranks of the Jedi Order, known for their ability to strip down and reassemble various types of technology. Additionally, details regarding ''mechu-deru'' were mentioned in [[The Jedi Path: A Manual for Students of the Force|''The Jedi Path'']], a guidebook intended for [[Jedi Initiate/Legends|Initiates]] of the Jedi Order.<ref name="TJP" /> In the time of the [[Extragalactic/Legends|extra-galactic]] [[Yuuzhan Vong War|Yuuzhan Vong invasion]], the [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Tam Azur-Jamin]] made references to ''mechu-deru'' in an essay entitled [[Droids, Technology and the Force: A Clash of Phenomena|''Droids, Technology and the Force'']]. The document explored the views held by the Jedi regarding ''mechu-deru'', as well as the concept of a relationship between mechanical constructs and the Force.<ref name="DTATF" />

==Behind the scenes==
''Mechu-deru'' was introduced in the novel [[Children of the Jedi]] in [[1995]].<ref name="COTJ" /> This concept was later added upon by [[Abel G. Peña]], an author who identified ''mechu-deru'' in an adventure seed—[[The Emperor's Pawns|''The Lost Art'']]—featured in the [[2001]] article entitled ''[[The Emperor's Pawns]]''.<ref name="EN-DATF">{{Blog|abelgpena|47|Endnotes for ''Droids, Technology and the Force: A Clash of Phenomena, Part I''}}</ref> The name of ''mechu-deru'' was taken from ''[[The Essential Guide to Episode I]]'',<ref name="EN-TEP">{{Blog|abelgpena|73|The Emperor's Pawns Endnotes, Part 1: Blackhole and Revelations}}</ref> a cancelled addition to the [[Star Wars: Essential Guides|''Essential Guide'']] series to be written by [[Daniel Wallace]].<ref name="TEGE1">{{Blog|danwallace|34|Lostwords: The Essential Guide to Episode I}}</ref> Additional backstory for ''mechu-deru'' was detailed by Wallace in ''[[The New Essential Guide to Droids]]'', a reference book published in [[2006]].<ref name="NEGD" /> While ''mechu-deru'' was named a dark side technique in ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'',<ref name="CSWE-DARZU" /> its use by the Jedi Order was later confirmed in another reference book called [[The Jedi Path: A Manual for Students of the Force (real-life book)|''The Jedi Path'']].<ref name="TJP" /> ''Mechu-deru'' was depicted unnamed in "[[Collapsing New Empires]]," a comic featured in the [[Star Wars Tales 19|nineteenth issue]] of the ''[[Star Wars Tales]]'' series.<ref name="CNE" /> This appearance was retconned in the final part of [[The Imperial Warlords: Despoilers of an Empire]], a [[StarWars.com]] blog series that concluded in [[2014]].<ref name="DOAE-3" />

